column24: Women's March; Women's March: Arlington; Women's March, October 17th, 2020, Arlington  2:00-3:30pm, Arlington MA    === https://fb.me/e/1wECpcbzL ===    Celebrate the 100th Anniversary of Women's Suffrage on the first day of Early Voting in Massachusetts. Join us for a socially distant, mask-wearing march for justice.     March for...    * Racial equality. Black Lives Matter. Stand with our fellow BIOPC citizens.  * Women's rights to our own bodies.  * Access to voting for all, for a fairer democracy.  * Fair, affordable healthcare for all.  * Our planet and the environment. Believe in science.  * Equal rights for LGBTQIA+ citizens.  * Freedom of religion, including freedom from religion.  * Immigrants' and refugees' rights. Families belong together.    The Women's March movement is led by women, including trans women, genderqueer women, and non-binary people who are significantly female-identified. People of all genders are invited to participate in and help organize our socially distanced Arlington Women's March.    === Schedule for Our March ===    * 2:00pm. Stand vigil on any location on Massachusetts Avenue in Arlington, on the sidewalk. Stay 6 feet or more from other protestors. Allow access to sidewalk ramps, and keep clear of business entrances.    * 2:15pm. Begin marching toward Arlington Center, while maintaining social distance (6’+). Arlington Center is located at the intersection of Mass Ave (Rt3) and Mystic St (Rt60), Arlington.    *As you approach Arlington Center, use your best judgment to maintain social distance. If it is safe to do so, walk past Arlington Town Hall at 730 Mass Ave*, then cross the street. Then, march toward your original locations.    * Please note that Arlington Town Hall sidewalk is currently under construction.  https://www.arlingtonma.gov/.../Comp.../News/News/10536/3977    * There may be pedestrian congestion near Town Hall. Keep marching as much as possible! Let’s minimize congestion, pass by each other quickly when necessary, and avoid close proximity for a prolonged period of time. Our priority is to march for human rights and social justice while keeping everybody safe from potential COVID-19 transmission.    * The march concludes once you return to your initial location. You may continue to stand vigil until 3:30pm, as a show of solidarity.    Thank you for fighting for social justice.    === https://fb.me/e/1wECpcbzL ===

column24: Women's March; Heel Talk Women’s March; Heel Talk LLC stands by all women from all walks of life, and all races, and believes that Women’s rights are human rights. We are all connected, we are sisters, we are all leaders in this world, we all have a voice, we all are capable, and we are all here to make that known and respected.     We believe in Reproductive Freedom, LGBTQIA rights, worker's rights, civil rights being our birthright, disability rights, immigration rights, rights to a clean and safe environment on all levels to all women.     This movement is just a start to social change and to encourage more and more women to stand up against the very things that are out to oppress us. We want more women to get involved in their communities to make sure we continue to create a better world for ourselves, our communities, and our families. The world needs us more each and every day, so come join us on this day to speak your mind on what you stand for!

column24: Women's March; Women’s March 2020; Together we will send an unmistakable message about the fierce opposition to Trump and his agenda, including his attempt to fill Ruth Bader Ginsburg’s seat.    Everyone is welcome! Please bring masks and stay with your group in an effort to maintain social distancing. Bring your signs to protest with! We are celebrating feminism in addition to protesting Trump's attempt to fill RBG's place.    We will do our utmost to make these events COVID-safe. We will ask all participants to wear masks and maintain social distancing, and we will require it of our organizers. We also suggest bringing water to stay hydrated!    We will engage and uplift the most impacted local communities in our organizing, programming, partnerships and outreach. This event  will be a representation of intersectional feminism; "exclusionary feminism" of any kind will not be tolerated.     We will graciously receive and incorporate feedback from all local marginalized communities.       We will adhere to principles of nonviolence in our approach and tactics. We understand that police signal danger to many communities. We will not invite police to participate in or speak at our actions beyond what is required by our permitting, including any capacity that would lead to “stop and frisk” type security. column24: Women's March; Women's March Cleveland March For Equality For All Women & Black Lives, & Against Confirmation Until Inauguration; https://www.facebook.com/events/235525221071344/  THIS OUTSIDE SOCIAL DISTANCING RALLY AND MARCH IS AN EVENT FOR ALL WOMEN ACROSS THE BOARD AND IS SAT., OCT 17, 2020, 1-3PM EASTERN STANDARD TIME: CONTACT TEL (216) 659-0473: Affiliated groups: Women's March Cleveland, International Women's Day March Cleveland, Black Women's PAC of greater Cleveland, National Congress of Black Women Greater Cleveland Chapter,  Imperial Women Coalition, CCDWC, Greater Cleveland Immigrant Support Network, Peace Action, Women Speak Out for Peace and Justice, Imperial Women Coalition, Clevelandurbannews. com, Black Votes Matter Cleveland, Refusefacism Ohio, Peace in the Hood, Finding Our Children-The Missing-Ebony Alert,  BEMAD, and more. We will march for Breonna Taylor and other Black women  erroneously killed by police.     The rally  is at 1pm on Sat., Oct 17, 2020  at the Harvard Community Services Center at 18240 Harvard Ave outside.  in Ward 1 on Cleveland's east side . It will be followed by a  2:15 pm march.      This Women's March Cleveland Justice March event is a social distancing march and is part of a national march for  equality for women, an event that will also address LGBTQ rights and Black lives in America and a  protest also regarding policies in Washington D.C. that are detrimental to women, Blacks and others. Also at issue is  the nomination by President Trump of Judge Amy Coney Barrett as his U.S. Supreme Court pick to replace the late and iconic Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg before the presidential election in November and the presidential inauguration in January 2021      Women's rights groups, clergy, elected officials, local activists,  Black women leaders and women across racial and ethic lines will speak, among others. If the president's Supreme Court nominee is confirmed before our Oct 17 rally and march we will urge consequences at the ballot box at the rally and march.    All progressive women and their supporters on this issue are invited . Please stand with women on this issue. Masks and social distancing required by city ordinance. In 2017, women made history when millions of us came together in the streets of Washington D.C. , in Cleveland and in cities across this country to rise up against inequalities against women, and to make our resistance clear. We need to rise up again on October 17 and finish the work we started three years ago.    Masks will be provided to those who need one free of charge.  Women will not go backwards. In the struggle, Women's March Cleveland

column24: Women's March; Women’s March Dallas; Together we will send an unmistakable message about the fierce opposition to Trump and his agenda, including his attempt to fill Ruth Bader Ginsburg’s seat.    Everyone is welcome! Please bring masks and stay with your group in an effort to maintain social distancing. Bring your signs to protest with! We are celebrating feminism in addition to protesting Trump's attempt to fill RBG's place.    We will do our utmost to make these events COVID-safe. We will ask all participants to wear masks and maintain social distancing, and we will require it of our organizers.    We will engage and uplift the most impacted local communities in our organizing, programming, partnerships and outreach. This event will be a representation of intersectional feminism; "exclusionary feminism" of any kind will not be tolerated.    We will graciously receive and incorporate feedback from all local marginalized communities.    We will adhere to principles of nonviolence in our approach and tactics.    We understand that police signal danger to many communities. We will not invite police to participate in or speak at our actions beyond what is required by our permitting, including any capacity that would lead to “stop and frisk” type security.    Know Your Rights: https://www.aclu.org/know-your-rights/protesters-rights/#im-attending-a-protest

column24: Women's March; Together We Rise Women’s March; Rather than a high capacity march in one location, we are TAKING OVER Randall Road!    Randall Rd. Stretches 28 miles from Aurora to Algonquin and passes through highly populated areas in the towns of Aurora, Batavia, Geneva, St. Charles, Elgin, and Algonquin.     To focus efforts in our local communities and be cautious about the spread of COVID-19, rather than mass attendance in one place, we chose to cover distance, and unite our communities instead!    Major intersections have been mapped out, and attendees are encouraged to pick an intersection, bring your friends, bring your signs, bring your children, bring your grandma! Women and allies will be holding signs to raise awareness within our communities.     Large crowds in a pandemic not your thing? No problem! There are 28 miles to cover, so you can easily post up at a less crowded intersection, or even on sidewalks between the rally points!     We are working with local woman and minority owned businesses in the area to make this event amazing!      Important info:  Here is the link to the Facebook event. You’ll find announcements, maps, sign up sheets, and volunteer opportunities.  https://facebook.com/events/s/together-we-rise-womens-march/1176174626112006/?ti=icl     ? Masks are required, and social distancing is encouraged   ? We are not disrupting traffic, closing intersections, or creating unsafe conditions for drivers or pedestrians.     We rise by lifting each other, and together we rise! <U+270A>?<U+270A>?<U+270A>?<U+270A>?<U+270A>?

column24: Women's March; Harrisburg PA Women's March Gathering; On October 17, 2020, Noon to 2 PM, there will be a gathering in support of the Women’s March in Washington, DC, at the Fountain Plaza of the Pennsylvania State Capitol (501 N 3rd St, Harrisburg, PA 17120).     This will be an opportunity to stand together against the destructive agenda of Donald Trump and those who support him.      In this time of national distress, we need to come together in supporting the highest ideals of the United States of America.   At this time, “Liberty and Justice for ALL” finally needs to mean every human being.       Please join us in celebrating Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg, standing against the dictatorship/theocracy that Trump supporters want, and standing with each other to declare that we are not going back.      The event will be on the Capitol Steps.  I had initially reserved the Fountain Plaza for its ease of access but the folks in charge said with the number of people (155 and counting!) we would be better on the steps. The Capitol Steps is on the Commonwealth Avenue side (west side right at the intersection of State Street and Third Street) of the Pennsylvania Capitol.   Parking will be free around the park on the other side of the capitol, Soldiers’ Grove, across Commonwealth Avenue, across from the fountain.  Stop and see the fountain anyway since it is dyed a lovely pink for Breast Cancer Awareness Month.    otherwise, parking will be for a fee on the streets and garages.  Info is here: https://parkharrisburg.com/      The steps are a very good venue, getting plenty of exposure but they are not conducive to folks with disabilities, being historical and not ADA compliant.  The sidewalk does come right up to them at the bottom.   The top drive is limited access for security reasons.      I am not going to have portable toilets because of the relatively short duration of the event.   Please pee before you come.  There are restaurants nearby but none will welcome the public just wandering in.  But they are great for a lunch!  The capitol will be open through the entrance at the top of the steps, but again, this is not accessible for disabled folks.  The PA capitol is gorgeous.      I am accessing a decent sound system so we can be heard.  We are looking for speakers. Please contact me.     Mask wearing and social distancing will be enforced.    Since it is close to Halloween, wear a costume of your favorite unruly woman.  :)  As for what to bring: a sign if you'd like:  nothing contraband;  a cushion of blanket if you'd like to sit on the steps or the walls around them, a couple places can also handle a foldable chair;  a hat if you are sensitive to the sun, something to drink if you'd like.   A bunch of restaurants are close by downtown.        The fountain at the Capitol will be dyed pink for Breast Cancer Awareness Month, so it should be a pretty venue.    We are Big Damn Heroes.

column24: Women's March; Women's March: Herndon, VA - RISE UP for You Rights!; Women's March is coming through Herndon, VA! Oct. 17, 2020 @3pm - 4:30pm  *Masks and practicing safe social distancing guidelines required*    ?JOIN US ? On October 17th — Women’s March is planning a massive, nationwide march to send an unmistakable message that we will not allow the current government administration to endanger our lives any longer. This is what we’ve been preparing for...this is why millions of women of all ages and their allies marched on January 21, 2017.  We are called to RISE UP to the urgency of this moment. We have to show up and march for ALL women – for Trans, Black, Indigenous, and Brown women, and for future generations.  In the wake of Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg’s passing, thousands of Women’s Marchers gathered across the country in their communities to honor the life and legacy of the Notorious RBG. Together, we showed the world that this movement is more committed and fired up than ever to carry on the fight for justice and equality that RBG championed for so many years.  NOW is the time to build on RGB's legacy, along with all the heroic women who came before her. We must go beyond words posts, and move into action with everything we have to protect the courts and defeat tyranny & injustice on November 3rd.  Let's rise up once again on October 17th to finish the work we started three years ago. This is our best shot to stop the criminals in charge from stacking the Supreme Court and silencing our voices for years to come.  We must give it everything we have!    Get up, stand up - RISE UP for your rights!

column24: Women's March; Women's March Coalition of East TN - Day of Action; The Women's March Coalition of Knoxville in conjunction with our community partners, Indivisible East Tennessee, and the Knox County Democratic Party, will participate in the Women's March national and statewide day of action with a local event.    Participants need to mask up and will be required to follow social distancing precautions as we continue to keep one another safe during the pandemic . There are also remote options available for those who are not comfortable with an in person event.    Locally, we will be having a two part approach to our day of action! At 10:00 a.m., we will be assembling downtown for a short rally at Krutch Park which will highlight what is at stake this election. Guest speakers will cover topics such as the Affordable Care Act, marriage equality, women's health and reproductive freedom and information on voting.    Next, we will march to the polls (City County Building, an early voting site) so that anyone who would like to may cast their vote early. (Please make sure you bring a photo ID and that you are able to cover up/remove any campaign related paraphernalia which is not allowed at the election poll site.)  After marching back to the rally site, we will then disburse for the second part of the Day of Action...    Our local, state and federal campaigns are down to the wire and need volunteers to text, phone bank, conduct literature drops, canvass, and deliver yard signs. We want to plug in the energy and people power of the Women's March to our area progressive campaigns.    Campaigns are currently organizing their individual Day of Action events for the afternoon of the 17th. They will be creating Facebook events for their actions and we will be linking those in the event page as they become available.  (You will be able to pick the way in which they would like to participate and which of the candidates you would like to support.)    We have rallied, marched and carried signs and while that is great for awareness and visibility, we wanted to find a way to make a direct impact.  So, join us on Saturday, October 17th to cast your vote with your friends, loved ones, and fellow Women's March resisters and then spend the afternoon volunteering on a campaign to make positive change!

column24: Women's March; Nationwide Lodi Sister March; We will be joining the nationwide call to action on October 17th in our city of Lodi. With her tragic death women in this country are now having their fundamental rights threatened by Donald Trump and his Supreme Court nominee Amy Coney Barrett. “My most fervent wish is that I will not be replaced until a new president is installed“- Ruth Bader Ginsburg. That was her dying wish and we believe in honor and respect we must do any and everything in our power to fulfill her dying wish. On October 17th we will be doing everything we can to fulfill her dying wish and to uphold and uplift her memory and legacy. We will fight in honor of Ruth! We will fight to protect women’s fundamental rights! Join Us if you can and bring your signs!

column24: Women's March; Women’s March Muncie; If you’re here, and reading this now, you know something is wrong. You know lives of women and the marginalized have become worse over the course of the past 4 years and the progress we have made as a nation and over many generations toward civility, gender and racial equality has become a question mark, in the face of unparalleled incivility, violence, mass misinformation and a global pandemic.    We are standing on the precipice of reversals of human and women’s rights.   We must work together to preserve civility, democracy and the integrity of our election.   In the middle of a global pandemic, local marches are advised; march with with us, here in Muncie.   Masks and social distancing are required.   Wear your masks, bring your voices, signs, families and neighbors.   The Women’s March in Muncie is a peaceful march for all; all families, all genders, all races, all political affiliations, all sexual orientations, and all creeds, to unite our voices and protect our community against the growing division and chaos that threatens democracy and our nation.   A growing list of supporting individuals, groups, organizations, legislators and/or speakers which will be updated accordingly.    Some of those groups and organizations are:  -Muncie Human Rights Commission  -Indiana 6th District Democratic Chair, Annette Craycraft   -Moms Demand Action  -Jeannine Lee Lake for Congress  -Planned Parenthood of Indiana and Kentucky  -Beneficence Family Scholars  -YWCA of Central Indiana  -Muncie OUTreach  -Muncie Resists   -Muncie Matters  -Muncie Voice/Middletown Media  -A Better Way  -Stonewall Democrats of Delaware County  Speakers include:  -Linda Lawson, Lieutenant Governor Candidate (D)  -State Representative Sue Errington (D)  -Dana Black, Former Chair, Stonewall Democrats of Indiana, Outreach Director, Indiana State Democratic Party  -Yvonne Thompson, Muncie Human Rights Commission  -Julie Snider, State Representative Candidate (D)  -Anitra Davis, Muncie City Councilwoman  -Destiny Donati, Muncie Central High School Student, Vocalist  Important covid-related update: locally, our cases are beginning to go up and we are watching this very carefully and communicating with sister marches. We will update everyone on Friday, when new data is released.  If we need to go to virtual, that's what we have to do.   Stay tuned and march on.    Have questions? Want to be included in our organizing effort?   Contact the March Organizer, Aimee Robertson-West, amwest@protonmail.com     Why does Muncie NEED a Women’s March?   Go on the record, submit a one sentence quote, in your own words and please include your name, pronoun, and title (optional!) to amwest@protonmail.com    Find us on Facebook and Instagram!   Let’s have a Women’s March!

column24: Women's March; Women's March Rim Country; This is a Women's March to honor Ruth Bader Ginsburg and to deman that her Supreme Court seat will be filled by the next admnistration.    Another Stand for Justice action – Women’s March 10-17-20:  In conjunction with a National Women’s March action, there will be an RBG March for Justice in Payson on Saturday, October 17, 2020 from 9:30-10:30 AM. We will meet along the sidewalks fronting highways 87/260, spreading from the Wells Fargo entrance on 260 up to the corner of the 87/260 intersection and then along 87 to the entrance of the parking area leading to the gym. Please park in the parking lot behind McDonalds. Those who do not want to/cannot march but want to participate, can bring a chair and display a sign. Those marching will cover a route along 260/87 to Bonita and back.  The march is supporting women’s rights, women’s health care under the ACA which is being challenged at the Supreme Court level in January, the bigotry shown by the Trump administration in nominating a candidate 37 days before the election, the important role that RBG played in making women’s lives better, and to urge people to Vote in November. To that end, here are some suggestions for signs:  VOTE – Tell them Ruth sent you  We Dissent! Stop the hypocrisy  No selection before election  Vote: Retake the Senate  Bad News for Healthcare  Fundamental Rights at Stake  Other ideas are welcome as long as they are not "attack" signs aimed at specific political entities. This is a PEACEFUL demonstration. There will be signs available that support voting and the rights of women. Please park responsibly, away from business parking, and wear a mask. We will be enforcing social distancing as well. Hope to see you there.

column24: Women's March; Women’s March; About women, the Women’s March is for everyone. We stand in unconditional solidarity with all oppressed people, irrespective of gender or sexual identity, disability, religious affiliation, race, or ethnicity.     This is a peaceful onward-to-victory rally designed to fortify women’s spirit and determination in these perilous times — AND TO HONOR RBG!    We must rise up to the urgency of this moment and send a clear message: THIS ADMINISTRATION’S TIME IS UP.    For four years, women, especially women of color, have been failed by this administration’s reckless and racist policies. For too long, the GOP has sidestepped their duty to the people. Even now, in the face of a global pandemic, our Republican leaders have made it clear that they will never fight for us.    We’ve had enough.     We must make our resistance loud and clear in these final days leading up to the Senate’s illegitimate Supreme Court nomination vote —and— the most consequential election of our life.    We’re marching (rallying) on October 17th, joining forces across the country for a massive day of action.     Dress to express yourself, and for comfort. Bring a sign or two. The sky’s the limit!    Social distancing and masks (covering nose and mouth) are required.     #IntersectionalFeminism #AllBlackLivesMatter #StrongerTogether

column24: Women's March; Sister March and Sign Holding Event; From Women's March:    "Women in this country are bearing the brunt of multiple crises, including  white supremacy and nationalism, a worsening climate crisis, an ever-deepening economic disaster, the global COVID-19 pandemic, and a family/domestic crisis. The most crucial election of our lifetimes is looming, and the current administration is threatening to stay in office no matter its outcome. In this state of emergency, the death of Ruth Bader Ginsburg is a lightning rod of clarity for many thousands of women to redouble our work for justice.     Why are we taking action on October 17?      We are all in to VOTE TRUMP OUT. As women, we know we are bearing the brunt of the multiple major crises we are living through. We are livid that Trump is rushing to fill Ruth Bader Ginsburg’s Supreme Court seat with an illegitimate and extremist nominee, and we are done with the death-dealing of this administration.     We are taking action across the nation on October 17 to signal and strengthen our determination to finish what we started when millions of women first marched in January 2017. We’ve resisted those in power for three years, and now we are taking power back. Women will decide this election, defend its integrity, and fight together for the feminist future we need."      Show up on October 17, 2020 in Roseville/Rocklin area and make your voice heard!    Bring your posters (self-made and otherwise) and masks, and spread out on the sidewalks.    It is our upmost priority to make this a safe event, so masks and distancing are required. Please stay on the sidewalks and out of traffic.     Happy creating and see you soon!

column24: Women's March; Women's March Sacramento; March with us on October 17, 2020 as we #ALLRISE for RBG. Our women. Our gender non-conformers. Our Democracy. For our lives here in Sacramento and throughout the world. Let us #ALLRISE in solidarity to ring loud and clear once again from here and all around the world on October 17 - to send an unmistakable message of our fierce opposition to this Administration and their oppressive agenda.     We ESPECIALLY stand against their abject disrespect towards Ruth Bader Ginsburg’s seat still warm with her fire and tenacious spirit. Sacramento also mourns the painful injustice and the precious loss of the life of dear Breonna Taylor and all Black womxn who fell before and after her - we call for their justice.  We RISE for freedom of reproductive choice. We RISE for family unification for immigrants, and we RISE for Trans access to healthcare. WE RISE AGAINST FORCED HYSTERECTOMIES.     Allied in spirit with Women’s March Global, we RISE for Compassion, Allyship, Respect, and Equity.  We RISE with Sacramento’s civil rights leaders, local activists, elected officials, women’s rights advocates, star performers, and super artists.    Together, WE RISE.    We invite you to RISE WITH US and join forces for Get Out The Vote (GOTV), Activism, and Action!     RISE WITH US.    We especially invite students and children to join us. We need the youth to RISE with us.    We observe social distancing measures to ensure COVID safety. Virtual Marching options will be available on #WomensMarchSac social media pages.    *Please check the disclaimer for rules per the Capitol and City required guidelines*    SUBSCRIBE FOR THE LATEST UPDATES  www.womensmarchsac.com/subscribe    Date: Saturday, October 17th, 2020  Location: Cesar Chavez Plaza    Schedule of Events  8:30AM- 9AM: Voting Resource Tables, Sign Making, and Live Stream Begins  9AM - 9:45AM: Women’s Social Justice Rally, “Solutions Only!”  9:45AM - 10:45AM: Marching Action with Absentee Ballots. Led by local community activists. Return to Cesar Chavez Plaza  10:45AM - 11:30AM: “All Rise!” Social Justice Rally and Ballot Action    Contingents: Coordinate, register your organization to be listed, and plan to meet at Cesar Chavez Plaza by 8:30AM for the voter resources, and to get a good “socially distant” group formation spot for the rally and march.     Please keep heavy traffic in mind. Rideshare (Uber, Lyft, Taxi) drop-off area to be announced.    March Route: Route length will be approximately one mile. The marching action will be hosted by EMPACT and local activist organizations on the ground. TBA    Rally: Speakers, music, and live performances begin at 9AM Cesar Chavez Plaza. A shuttle for marchers with disabilities will be available. “Virtual March” options will be available on #WomensMarchSac Social Media Accounts with more details to be announced.    Parking: We encourage marchers to carpool, take regional transit or the 42 Yolo Bus from Davis and Woodland, and to reserve parking. Organizers from Woodland and Davis - please email Jose at Yolo Bus about the route to plan large groups at jperez@ycpd.org or call 530-402-2826. Special Parking passes for volunteers, will be announced via email. Blue Placard Disabled parking, bus parking, large carpools, and Ride-Share Drop Off (Uber, Lyft, Taxi) to be announced.    The Sacramento Police Department has let us know that parking regulations surrounding Cesar Chavez Plaza and the march route will be strictly enforced.    Accessibility: Additional Blue Placard Disabled parking locations to be announced. There will be a special lane marked with a Blue Placard for wheelchairs and a ramp that leads to seating for marchers with disabilities near a First Aid tent. The sign language interpreters will be in the livestream shot at all times. Masks are required at all times. Extra masks will be available in the First Aid and Information Tents. More accessibility information will be posted soon.    Although registration is not required to attend the event, we’re asking for participants to register on www.womensmarchsac.com/info so we can have an accurate count to plan for proper accommodations.    Disclaimer: Please keep 6 feet of social distance from any person who is not in your household and wear a face mask to cover your nose and mouth. Please limit sticks on signs or flags to 18 inches of wood from the bottom of the sign or flag. By choosing to attend this event, you are acknowledging the risks involved, and you are committing to participate nonviolently and in accordance with the law, and to work to de-escalate confrontations with counter protesters or others.    You agree (i) not to engage in any act of violence or violation of any applicable law, (ii) to obey the orders of authorized event marshals and law enforcement authorities, (iii) that Women’s March Sacramento organizers and affiliate organizations will not be responsible for any injury or damage to your person or property resulting from or occurring in the course of your participating in the event; and you agree to release and forever hold harmless Women’s March Sacramento, affiliated organizations, and their respective officers, directors, employees and agents from liability for any such injury or damage.

column24: Women's March; I Am Woman, Hear Me Roar – San Diego Women's March; Join more than 200 San Diego residents as we co-create a sister march in San Diego, Ca.    This march welcomes anyone regardless of gender, skin color, or sexual orientation.    We'll meet on the lawn of President's Way Parking Lot in Balboa Park.     After a short speech, we'll march into the street, IN FRONT OF TRAFFIC, and head to high-profile POI's in San Diego.     We'll chant at some point during the march and observe silence at other times.    If you haven't attended a protest before, walking in the road can be a bit disconcerting at first. But then you'll feel empowered.     Remember, we're here to make an impact and be noticed!    The exact route is TBD by the number of participants, our energy, etc.     You can leave the march at any time you feel it becomes too much for you. Please be sure you have a ride on stand-by or quit at a point where you can make the return trip.    There will be no snacks, water, or other beverages available at the event since there wasn't time to organize refreshments.     Please eat a nutritious meal of complex carbohydrates, healthy protein, and fat to sustain you through the march, and make sure to hydrate well!    This is a no-trash event!!! Please don't bring packaged snacks or bottled water unless they're in re-usable containers.    Please bring plenty of water for yourself in non-disposable bottles, sunscreen, a hat, and anything else you need to feel comfortable. It's going to be warm.     Again – This is a no-waste event!!        COVID-19 Precautions:    Masks are required. You must wear a mask that fits well and stays put over your nose and mouth.     Anyone who displays a lack of concern for others' safety will be kindly asked to leave the group.    Chin diapers don't protect anyone. Masks that fall off your nose don't protect anyone.     Disposable hospital-style masks are cooler and easiest to breathe through. If you use one, be sure to break the straps before you throw it away so that animals don't get caught in them. They are bio-degradable.    Also, we'll all do the best we can to socially distance and still form a cohesive and powerful body of women.     But, you're taking a risk by participating.     Outdoor risk is lower than indoor, but there's still risk involved.     If you have chronic health issues that put you at high risk of developing a severe case of COVID 19, should you be exposed, it may be best to skip the march.    Please bring a sign if you like.     I look forward to making an impact with you.    Cheers    Janet

column24: Women's March; March for Our Rights (Official Women's March San Francisco); Official Women's March San Francisco (WMSF)!     #MarchForOurRights on Saturday October 17th at 11 AM @ Grove & Hyde St and Virtually!!    Hosted by League of Women Voters SF, NARAL Pro-Choice California, Planned Parenthood Northern California, San Francisco Women’s Political Committee, The Women’s Building of San Francisco and Women’s March San Francisco (digital co-host)    RSVP & SHARE OUR OFFICIAL POSTINGS!!  Facebook Link: https://fb.me/e/4v68lE3mL   Eventbrite Link: https://www.eventbrite.com/e/march-for-our-rights-tickets-124360715247    Follow Our Social Media to stay posted:   IG & Twitter = @wmarchsf     Facebook = @sfwomensmarch  Website = https://womensmarchsf.org/    If you haven't already done so #VoteEarly DROP OFF your filled out and signed Ballot at Bill Graham Auditorium Voting Center or any USPS Mailbox and come MARCH WITH US!    MARCH: Line up BY 11am for this social distance March at Grove St between Larkin and Hyde St to March; we will march down Market Street to Embarcadero Plaza. We will NOT have an in person Rally before or after the March and we ask the community's help to disperse at the end of the march.    VIRTUAL: WMSF presents Live Stream Virtual Call To Action starting around 11:05 AM as an option for those who cannot attend the in person march. Link from http://www.womensmarchsf.org/marchforourrights (note: link is currently set to the recording of last year’s WMSF rally and will be updated on 10/17 once we go live). Follow-us on our social media or website for the links and more information.       We demand:  ~No Appointment Until AFTER Inauguration  ~Protect Marriage Equality  ~Protect Women’s Right to Choose  ~Black Lives Matter      Vote for:  ENDING VIOLENCE  REPRODUCTIVE JUSTICE  LGBTQI+ RIGHTS  WORKERS RIGHTS  CIVIL RIGHTS  DISABILITY RIGHTS  IMMIGRANT RIGHTS  ENVIRONMENTAL JUSTICE      Call to Action:  ~Register to Vote (by Oct 19th, Voter Registration will be available at Bill Graham Auditorium Voting Center on 10/17 from 10am - 4pm )  ~Vote Early (Oct 5th - Nov 2nd)  ~Drop off your filled out and signed Ballot at USPS Mailbox or at Bill Graham Auditorium Voting Center on 10/17 and come March with us!  ~Volunteer at Voting Booth (https://sfelections.sfgov.org/serving-poll-worker)       We honor and remember:  ~Commemorating the 215,000+ lives lost due to Covid-19 in the United States #MournOutLoud  ~Breonna Taylor, George Floyd, Tony McDade, Trayvon Martin, Tamir Rice, Michael Brown, Eric Garner, Philando Castile, Oscar Grant and many others Black and Brown souls lost due to police brutality. #BlackLivesMatter    Bring your family, friends, signs, water, sunscreen, and hat and dress with layers and comfy shoes. Check the weather!    *Masks are Required*  **No Rally at the Beginning or End of the March**  ***March will be canceled if we are at Orange/Red quality air index***  ****This is a 1st Amendment march, no host is liable, march at your own risk****    #MarchForOurRights  #WomensMarchSanFrancisco  #RegisterToVote  #VoteEarly    ---  We acknowledge that we are on the unceded ancestral homeland of the Ramaytush Ohlone who are the original inhabitants of the San Francisco Peninsula.  ---      Women's March San Francisco (WMSF) is a grassroots organization run by 100% volunteers only, we are self created, self managed, and self funded, and have been since our creation on November 19, 2016. WMSF is led by local community activists working to unify and empower everyone who stands for human rights, civil liberties, and social justice for all through intersectionality and community work.    We do not receive any funding from, nor are we affiliated with, Women’s March DC Chapter (aka: “National” / Inc.), Women's March Foundation & Action (aka: LA chapter) or Women’s March California; we rely solely on donations and support directly from our community. https://womensmarchsf.org/

In winding up the hour we will line the El Camino raising our placards. Bring a sign to let the passing motorists know how we feel and encourage honking! Any pro-woman, pro-peace and justice message is OK, and let's emphasize fierce opposition to Trump and his agenda, including his attempt to fill  Ruth Bader Ginsburg’s seat.

column24: Women's March; Stamford Women's March to Save Democracy; STAMFORD WOMEN’S MARCH TO SAVE DEMOCRACY!    MARCH WITH US ON OCTOBER 17.    Join PinkWave, Stamford Women's Talking Circle, The S.W.A.T. Team - Suburban Women Against Trump, Stronger Together CT, community leaders, and concerned citizens to RISE UP and march to #SaveDemocracy!    NOTE LOCATION CHANGE: Our Stamford Women's March will take place in its entirety at 10:30 AM the Stamford-Norwalk Superior Courthouse at 123 Hoyt Street, Stamford, CT. column24: Women's March; Women's March Tucson; As we all know, yesterday Trump nominated Amy Coney Barrett to fill RBG’s seat on the Supreme Court. We all need to stay healthy enough to make it to the polls in November!

In Miami, we will be marching with a purpose, getting out the vote and making sure communities are heard at the ballot box on November 3rd. We will gather at Women's March Miami's base camp in Wynwood to be inspired by your favorite femme candidates/community leaders and receive literature about early voting, mail in ballots and issues vital to all women with a stake in this election. Our #WhyWeVote campaign is about healthcare, this pandemic, Black, Native and LGBTQIA+ lives, clean air and water, education and our bodies. Folks will be grouped and assigned locations, and we will talk to women about why they need to vote and who they need to vote for in support of our ability to thrive. We'll have our 2020 "Breaking Our Chains" shirts beautifully designed by LeoArt available for our "marchers" as supplies last. Face masks are mandatory. Please wear comfortable shoes and be prepared for Miami weather (bring sunglasses, a hat, sunscreen and rain gear). We will also have a phone banking station and sign waving stations.    We're happy to have you at our Wynwood (base camp) location, but you can also host your own event at your chosen location that same day to bring the march to your community! You can also host a watch party of our rally before your folks get their boots on the ground!    To participate, complete our RSVP/Volunteer form:   https://forms.gle/1RDpTnM92cgWpZ7z5    Rally: 12pm to 1pm  GOTV Activities: 1pm to 4pm
